        <p>In October 1896, the regiment was sent to India and quartered in Bangalore. Churchill reads a lot, trying to compensate for the lack of a university education, and becomes one of the best players of the regiment's polo team. According to the reminiscences of his subordinates, he was conscientious about his officer's duties and spent a lot of time working with hussars and sergeants, but the routine of service weighed on him, twice he went on vacation to England (including for celebrations on the occasion of the 60th anniversary of the reign of Queen Victoria), traveled around India, visited Calcutta and Hyderabad.</p>
        <p>On November 15, Churchill went on a reconnaissance raid on an armored train commanded by Captain Haldane (English Haldane), an acquaintance of his from Malakand. Soon the armored train was shelled by the Boer artillery. When trying to get out of the fire at high speed in reverse, the train crashed into boulders with which the enemy blocked the way to cut off the retreat. The repair platform and two armored cars derailed, the only weapon of the immobile armored train was disabled by a direct hit.</p>
